VegDescription: sclerophyllous forests with evergreen Quercus accompanied by Laurus nobilis. The degradation of these forests corresponds to mattorals where Quercus ilex forests dominate. The Supra-Mediterranean belt is mainly composed of Quercus pubescens associated to Buxus sempervirens. The temperate zone corresponds to deciduous oak mixed forests in plains (< 700 m). The temperate hills and mountains i.e. the northern part of the Alps as well as the Massif Central is characterized by the development of Fagus from 700 to 1000 m high. Fagus is mixed with Abies in higher mountains. Mountainous forests of conifers occur from 1450 to 2500 m high. The Alpine belt begins at ca. 2000-2300 m. The lower part is composed of Ericaceae or alpine grassland with Poaceae, Fabaceae and Cyperaceae

VegDescription: Mixed coppice beneath a canopy of mainly Quercus and Betula standards. The coppiced stools consist predominantly of Corylus avellana and Fraxinus excelsior, though unusually Alnus glutinosa is co-dominant over an area of about 40 ha.  Primula elatior, Filipendula ulmaria and Mercurialis perennis are common in the ground flora, with Rubus spp., Pteridium aquilinum and Hyacinthoides non-scriptus also common.
Publication1: Waller, M.P., Grant, M.J. and Bunting, M.J. (in prep.) Identifying woodland management in the pollen record: the influence of coppicing. To be submitted to Journal of Ecology.

VegDescription: Area of open heath with surrounding softwood and hardwood plantations, including Pinus sylvestris, P. nigra, Pseudotsuga menziesii, Picea abies, Quercus and Fagus sylvestris. Mire vegetation is dominated by a central valley channel dominated by Molinia caerulea, Eriophorum angustifolium, with Myrica gale and Juncus acutiflorus. Margins of the mire compose a large area of step mireconsisting of Sphagnum lawn. Areas are frequently colonised by Ulex europaeus and Pinus sylvestris and encroachment of Pteridium aquilinum
Publication1: Grant, M.J. (2005). The Palaeoecology of Human Impact in the New Forest. Unpublished PhD thesis, University of Southampton.

VegDescription: Large valley mire situated within an area of open heathland with surrounding mixed woodland and plantations comprising principally Quercus robur, Q. petraea, Fagus sylvatica and Pinus sylvestris with Larix decidua, Pseudotsuga menziesii, Tsuga heterophylla, Pinus nigra and Picea sitchensis also present. Mire vegetation is dominated by a Sphagnum carpet of S. auriculatum and S. cuspidatum. Molinia caerulea, Eriophorum angustifolium, Juncus acutiflorus, Erica tetralix are abundant, with Rhynchospora alba and Eleocharis multicaulis also frequent in parts of the site
Publication1: Grant, M.J. (2005). The Palaeoecology of Human Impact in the New Forest. Unpublished PhD thesis, University of Southampton.

VegDescription: Part of a large valley mire system situated within an area of open heathland with several small stands of Ilex aquifolium, Pinus sylvestris and Betula pendula, with larger deciduous and softwood plantations c. 1km to the south and south west. Coring location was within open tussocky Molinia community with Eriophorum angustifolium abundant. To the south along the axis of drainage Salix carr woodland is present with Carex paniculata, Lysimachia vulgaris, Myrica gale, Glyceria fluitans, Dryopteris austriaca and widespread Sphagnum squarrosum lawn.
Publication1: Grant, M.J. (2005). The Palaeoecology of Human Impact in the New Forest. Unpublished PhD thesis, University of Southampton.

VegDescription: Site is set within predominantly open heathland with some Betula pendula scrub, surronded by mixed plantations, natural woodland stands and valley mires. Site vegetation is very wet Sphagnum lawn compossed mainly of S. papilosum and S. recurvum, with some S. cuspidatum, Eriophorum angustifolium, Erica tetralix, Molinia caerulea and scattered Myrica gale.
Publication1: Grant, M.J. (2005). The Palaeoecology of Human Impact in the New Forest. Unpublished PhD thesis, University of Southampton.

VegDescription: Large raised bog, predominantly Spagnum lawn with Calluna vulgaris, Erica tertralix and Eriophorum vaginatum the main plant types. Situated within an area of open uplands which is heavily grazed, but patches of mixed woodland and wood fen are found along the northern edge of the mire.

VegDescription: Quercus robur is the main standard species, though other species including Tilia cordata, Carpinus betulus and Castanea sativa are also present as maidens. Coppiced Tilia cordata is abundant with, in some areas, Castanea sativa co-dominant. Small but distinct areas with coppiced Carpinus betulus, Fraxinus excelsior, Acer campestre or Corylus avellana co-dominant as the coppiced species also occur. The ground vegetation is dominated by Hyacinthoides non-scripta with Rubus spp. and Pteridium aquilinum also locally abundant.
Publication1: Waller, M.P., Grant, M.J. and Bunting, M.J. (in prep.) Identifying woodland management in the pollen record: the influence of coppicing. To be submitted to Journal of Ecology.

VegDescription: Sample taken within an area of Alnus glutinosa carr woodland. Open areas of the mire to the north are dominated by Juncus acutiflorus over a carpet of Sphagnum recurvum. To the south-west, open areas are dominated by Agrostis canina with Carex paniculata and Carex remota, with patches of Myrica gale abundant. The surrounding dryland is dominated by a mixture of mature ancient woodland comprising a mixture of Quercus sp. and Fagus sylvatica, many of the later having been pollarded. Also common is an understorey of Ilex aquifolium. Adjacent to patches of ancient woodland are more recent plantations comprising Fagus sylvatica, Quercus, Pinus sylvestris and Picea abies. The local area is heavily grazed by cattle, ponies and deer
Publication1: Grant, M.J. (2005). The Palaeoecology of Human Impact in the New Forest. Unpublished PhD thesis, University of Southampton.
Publication2: Grant, M.J. and Edwards, M.E. (2008). Conserving Idealized Landscapes: Past History, Public Perception and Future Management. Vegetation History and Archaeobotany, 17, 551-562.
Publication3: Edwards, M.E. and Grant, M.J. (2011). Long-term perspectives on an iconic landscape: Origins and future trajectories of the "Ancient and Ornamental Woodland", New Forest, UK. PAGES News, 19, 2, 51-53
Publication4: Grant, M.J., Barber, K.E. and Hughes, P.D.M. (2009b). True Ancient Woodland? 10,000 years of continuous woodland cover at Mark Ash Wood, New Forest. In: B. Briant, M. Bates, R.T. VegDescription: Large valley mire with well developed Sphagnum lawns, consisting predominantly of S. papilosum with a number of other Sphagna present. Molinia caerulea, Narthecium, Erica tetralix and Eriophorum angustifolium are abundant. Flushing zones along the edge of the mire are dominated by Schoenus nigrcans, with Cirsium dissectum frequent in other areas of the mire. Surrounding dryland is dominated by open dry and wet heathland and extensive shallow valley mire deposits. Close to the mire are stands of Pinus sylvestris. Stands of ancient woodland containing mixed Quercus robur and Fagus sylvatica are located c. 0.5km to the east of the mire.
Publication1: Grant, M.J. (2005). The Palaeoecology of Human Impact in the New Forest. Unpublished PhD thesis, University of Southampton.

VegDescription: Ombrotrophic bog, still growing, raised bog species, including Vaccinium oxycoccus and Andromeda polifolia. Dominant elements are Sphagnum magellanicum, S. rubellum, S. angustifolium, Eriophorum angustifolium and E. vaginatum. Small Betula on bog. Area around the maar: ~1.7 ha deciduous forest, ~0.9 ha coniferous forest and relatively little pasture (Forst et al., 1997). Arable land exists beyond the maar crater slopes but not in direct proximity to the bog.
Publication1: Kuehl N, Moschen R, Wagner S, Brewer S, Peyron O. 2010. A multiproxy record of Late Holocene natural and anthropogenic environmental change from the Sphagnum peat bog Durres Maar, Germany: implications for quantitative climate reconstructions based on pollen. Journal of Quaternary Science, 25: 675-688.
Worker1_Address1: Steinmann-Institute of Geology, Mineralogy and Paleontology, University of Bonn, Nussallee 8, 53115 Bonn, Germany
Worker2_Address1: Steinmann-Institute of Geology, Mineralogy and Paleontology, University of Bonn, Nussallee 8, 53115 Bonn, Germany

VegDescription: Ombrotrophic bog, not growing, with trees, on bog 1997: Picea abies (20m), Betula pubescens (10m); shrub layer: Sorbus aucuparia, Picea abies, Pinus sylvestris, Frangula alnus; ground vegetation layer includes Vaccinium myrtillus, Dryopteris dilatata, D. carthusiana, Trientalis europaea, Molinia caerulea. Around bog: Pteridium aquilinum with Corydalis claviculata, Galiuim hercynicum. Partition in which bog is located: Pinus, Fagus, Quercus; Rubus ideaus, Oxalis acetosella, Hieracium, seedlings of variety of trees. Partition further south with planted Picea and Larix. Partition further east with planted Pseudotsuga, Picea, Abies.
Notes: Samples: First cm from bog surface.
Publication1: Kuehl N. 1998. Pollenanalytische Untersuchungen zur Vegetations- und Siedlungsgeschichte in einem Kesselmoor bei Drangstedt, Ldkr. Cuxhaven. Probleme der Kustenforschung im sudlichen Nordseegebiet, 25: 303-324.
Worker1_Address1: Steinmann-Institute of Geology, Mineralogy and Paleontology, University of Bonn, Nussallee 8, 53115 Bonn, Germany

SiteName: Central Forest State Natural Biosphere Reserve, southern Valdai hills
VegDescription: Piceeta nemoraliosa - The forests in this group occur in the upper part of the relief on relatively rich soil. Their most important characteristic is the presence in the tree and shrub layers of broad-leaved species, such as Corylus avellana, Tilia cordata, Ulmus, Fraxinus excelsior). An understorey of Corylus avellana, Lonicera xylosteum and Sorbus aucuparia is usually well developed. In the rather abundant field layer, mesophytic herbs are prominent. The moss cover, unlike the other vegetationtypes, is poorly developed or absent.
Publication1: E.Y. Novenko (Ed.) Forest ecosystem dynamics of the south of Valdai Hills in the late Pleistocene and Holocene. Moscow, GEOS, 2011. 112 p.
Worker1_Address1: Institute of Geography of RAS, Moscow, Staromonetny lane, 29, Russia, 119017

SiteName: Central Forest State Natural Biosphere Reserve, southern Valdai hills
VegDescription: Piceeta hylocomiosa - These vegetation types are prevail in plant cover of the CFSNBR. These forests have a dense cover of mosses (30-35%, Pleurozium schreberi, Hylocomium splendens). There is no understorey, but the field layer is well developed. Its structure and species composition are closely correlated with soil conditions. The common species are Oxalis acetosella, Maianthemum bifolium, Vaccinium myrtillus, V. vitis-idaea, Linnaea borealis.
Publication1: E.Y. Novenko (Ed.) Forest ecosystem dynamics of the south of Valdai Hills in the late Pleistocene and Holocene. Moscow, GEOS, 2011. 112 p.
Worker1_Address1: Institute of Geography of RAS, Moscow, Staromonetny lane, 29, Russia, 119017

SiteName: Central Forest State Natural Biosphere Reserve, southern Valdai hills
VegDescription: Piceeta uliginoso-herbosa - This group of vegetation types is characteristically connected with Mezha river valley and its tributaries. Forest stands include Picea, Betula, Alnus glutinosa, A. incana, Salix caprea, rare Fraxinus excelsior. An understorey consists of Frangula alnus, Ribes nigrum, Viburnum opulus and often of Corylus avellana The herb layer is dense, high and rich in species (Aconitum septentrionale, Cinna latifolia, Mercurialis perennis, Aihyrium filix-femina, Dryopteris carthusiana, Poa remota, Cirsium oleraceum). In the most favorite habitats broad-leaved trees (Tilia cordata, Ulmus) take part in the forest stands and understorey.
Publication1: E.Y. Novenko (Ed.) Forest ecosystem dynamics of the south of Valdai Hills in the late Pleistocene and Holocene. Moscow, GEOS, 2011. 112 p.
Worker1_Address1: Institute of Geography of RAS, Moscow, Staromonetny lane, 29, Russia, 119017

SiteName: Central Forest State Natural Biosphere Reserve, southern Valdai hills
VegDescription: Piceeta sphagnosa - This group is characteristic of poorly drained and rather wet sites with flat relief. The stands are mainly composed of Picea spp. with an admixture of Betula.  The Sphagnum type of spruce forest has usually two layers, the sparse spruce stand and the ground layer of Sphagnum spp. (S. capillifolium, S. centrale, S. magellanicum, S. palustre and S. squarrosum). Among herbs in this type of forest Vaccinium myrtillus is common, and on small mounds Linnaea borealis and V. vitis-idaea.
Publication1: E.Y. Novenko (Ed.) Forest ecosystem dynamics of the south of Valdai Hills in the late Pleistocene and Holocene. Moscow, GEOS, 2011. 112 p.
Worker1_Address1: Institute of Geography of RAS, Moscow, Staromonetny lane, 29, Russia, 119017

Their most important characteristic is the presence in the tree and shrub layers of broad-leaved species, such as Corylus avellana, Tilia cordata, Ulmus, Fraxinus excelsior). An understorey of Corylus avellana, Lonicera xylosteum and Sorbus aucuparia is usually well developed. In the rather abundant field layer, mesophytic herbs are prominent. The moss cover, unlike the other vegetationtypes, is poorly developed or absent.
Publication1: E.Y. Novenko (Ed.) Forest ecosystem dynamics of the south of Valdai Hills in the late Pleistocene and Holocene. Moscow, GEOS, 2011. 112 p.
Worker1_Address1: Institute of Geography of RAS, Moscow, Staromonetny lane, 29, Russia, 119017

SiteName: Central Forest State Natural Biosphere Reserve, southern Valdai hills
VegDescription: Piceeta uliginoso-herbosa - This group of vegetation types is characteristically connected with Mezha river valley and its tributaries. Forest stands include Picea, Betula, Alnus glutinosa, A. incana, Salix caprea, rare Fraxinus excelsior. An understorey consists of Frangula alnus, Ribes nigrum, Viburnum opulus and often of Corylus avellana The herb layer is dense, high and rich in species (Aconitum septentrionale, Cinna latifolia, Mercurialis perennis, Aihyrium filix-femina, Dryopteris carthusiana, Poa remota, Cirsium oleraceum). In the most favorite habitats broad-leaved trees (Tilia cordata, Ulmus) take part in the forest stands and understorey.
Publication1: E.Y. Novenko (Ed.) Forest ecosystem dynamics of the south of Valdai Hills in the late Pleistocene and Holocene. Moscow, GEOS, 2011. 112 p.
Worker1_Address1: Institute of Geography of RAS, Moscow, Staromonetny lane, 29, Russia, 119017

SiteName: Central Forest State Natural Biosphere Reserve, southern Valdai hills
VegDescription: Piceeta sphagnosa - This group is characteristic of poorly drained and rather wet sites with flat relief. The stands are mainly composed of Picea spp. with an admixture of Betula.  The Sphagnum type of spruce forest has usually two layers, the sparse spruce stand and the ground layer of Sphagnum spp. (S. capillifolium, S. centrale, S. magellanicum, S. palustre and S. squarrosum). Among herbs in this type of forest Vaccinium myrtillus is common, and on small mounds Linnaea borealis and V. vitis-idaea.
Publication1: E.Y. Novenko (Ed.) Forest ecosystem dynamics of the south of Valdai Hills in the late Pleistocene and Holocene. Moscow, GEOS, 2011. 112 p.
Worker1_Address1: Institute of Geography of RAS, Moscow, Staromonetny lane, 29, Russia, 119017

SiteName: Central Forest State Natural Biosphere Reserve, southern Valdai hills
VegDescription: Piceeta hylocomiosa - These vegetation types are prevail in plant cover of the CFSNBR. These forests have a dense cover of mosses (30-35%, Pleurozium schreberi, Hylocomium splendens). There is no understorey, but the field layer is well developed. Its structure and species composition are closely correlated with soil conditions. The common species are Oxalis acetosella, Maianthemum bifolium, Vaccinium myrtillus, V. vitis-idaea, Linnaea borealis.
Publication1: E.Y. Novenko (Ed.) Forest ecosystem dynamics of the south of Valdai Hills in the late Pleistocene and Holocene. Moscow, GEOS, 2011. 112 p.
Worker1_Address1: Institute of Geography of RAS, Moscow, Staromonetny lane, 29, Russia, 119017

VegDescription: Relict broad-leaved formations occurred in the lowland (below1500 m), with conifers over 1300 m; spruce (Picea abies (L.) Karsten)-dominated formations with larch (Larix deciduas Miller) developed at 1500-1800 m. Larch-dominated woods (1800 and 2150 m), with shrubs such as Rhododendron ferrugineum L., Vaccinium myrtillus L., Juniperus communis L., and herbs forming the understory above 2000 m. The larches gave place over 2300m to shrub-dominated communities with Salix hastata L. and typical alpine pasture taxa like Trifolium alpinum L., Carex curvula All., Nardus stricta L. and Leontodon pyrenaicus Gouan ssp. helveticus Finch. The upper limit for isolated trees was around 2415 m, and above this alpine pastures became dominant. Above 2500m plant communities were dominated by Poaceae and Cyperaceae and characterised by typical alpine herbaceous taxa (Silene acaulis (L.) Jacq., Trifolium alpinum, Myosotis alpestris gr., Alchemilla vulgaris gr., Gentiana verna L., Leucanthemopsis alpina (L.) Heywood, Viola tricolor L., Sagina sp., Saxifraga sp., Rumex alpinus L., Trifolium pratense L. ssp. Frigidum Gaudin, Artemisia glacialis L.).

VegDescription: Broad-leaved formations with Quercus, Carpinus, Tilia, Castanea (below 1000 m), Fagus woods with Acer, Fraxinus, Corylus (below 1300 m), Picea woods (below 1800 m), open conifer formations with shrubs in the understory (Picea abies, Pinus cembra, Rhododendron ferrugineum, Vaccinium myrtillus) and alder formations (Alnus viridis (Chaix) DC., Rumex arifolius All., Geranium sylvaticum L.) LocationNotes: Point placed according to description and figures in ref. paper (Fig. 2 in ref paper is flipped horizontally). (MZ)
SiteDescription: Located in the low-alpine belt, on the terminal moraine that has been dated to c. AD 1750.
VegDescription: Heath community. Dense ericaceous heath, dominated by dwarf shrubs such as Empetrum nigrum, Vaccinium vitis-idaea, V. myrtillus, Phyllodoce caerulea and Betula nana. A variety of late successional herbs are present including Juncus trifidus, Pinguicula vulgaris, Bartsia alpina and Tofieldia pusilla. The vegetation cover is c. 95%.
Publication1: Pardoe, H.S. (1996) Micro-scale patterns of modern pollen deposition within three alpine plant communities. New Phytologist, 132, 327-341.
Worker1_Address1: Department of Biodiversity and Systematic Biology, National Museum Wales, Cathays Park, Cardiff, CF10 3NP, UK

LocationNotes: Point placed according to description and figures in ref. paper (Fig. 2 in ref paper is flipped horizontally). (MZ)
SiteDescription: Located on the 1930 moraine in the mid-alpine belt. The site is located close to a large melt-water stream and adjacent to a semi-permanent snow patch.
VegDescription: Salix-shrub community. The vegetation consists of a low dense scrub, dominated by shrub willows such as Salix glauca, S. phylicifolia and S. herbacea. Several herbs are also present including Festuca ovina, Deschampsia alpina, Carex spp. and Oxyria digyna. At this site there is c. 80% vegetation cover.
Publication1: Pardoe, H.S. (1996) Micro-scale patterns of modern pollen deposition within three alpine plant communities. New Phytologist, 132, 327-341.
Worker1_Address1: Department of Biodiversity and Systematic Biology, National Museum Wales, Cathays Park, Cardiff, CF10 3NP, UK

LocationNotes: Point placed according to description and figures in ref. paper (Fig. 2 in ref paper is flipped horizontally). (MZ)
SiteDescription: Mid- alpine belt on fluted moraines near the snout of Storbreen. This terrain has been deglaciated since 1951. The till substrate is disturbed by frequent freeze-thaw cycles and the sites are extremely exposed.
VegDescription: Pioneer community. The sparse vegetation, rarely exceeding a cover of 40%, consists of small clumps of moss and herbs such as Saxifraga nivalis, S. cespitosa, Oxyria digyna, Ranun- culus glacialis, Cerastium cerastoides, Phleum alpinum, Deschampsia alpina and Poa alpina.
Publication1: Pardoe, H.S. (1996) Micro-scale patterns of modern pollen deposition within three alpine plant communities. New Phytologist, 132, 327-341.
Worker1_Address1: Department of Biodiversity and Systematic Biology, National Museum Wales, Cathays Park, Cardiff, CF10 3NP, UK

LocationNotes: Point placed according to description and figures in ref. paper (Fig. 2 in ref paper is flipped horizontally). (MZ)
SiteDescription: Located in the low-alpine belt, on the terminal moraine that has been dated to c. AD 1750.
VegDescription: Heath community. Dense ericaceous heath, dominated by dwarf shrubs such as Empetrum nigrum, Vaccinium vitis-idaea, V. myrtillus, Phyllodoce caerulea and Betula nana. A variety of late successional herbs are present including Juncus trifidus, Pinguicula vulgaris, Bartsia alpina and Tofieldia pusilla. The vegetation cover is c. 95%.
Publication1: Pardoe, H.S. (1996) Micro-scale patterns of modern pollen deposition within three alpine plant communities. New Phytologist, 132, 327-341.
Worker1_Address1: Department of Biodiversity and Systematic Biology, National Museum Wales, Cathays Park, Cardiff, CF10 3NP, UK
